<subSubSection id="59F4654C560A6949C8DC0122801FF948" pageId="5" pageNumber="65" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="115136C7560A6949C8DC0122801FF948" blockId="5.[151,1437,1562,1877]" pageId="5" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560A6949C8DC01228253F9D4" bold="true" box="[199,324,1598,1624]" pageId="5" pageNumber="65">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
As discussed in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560A6949C9E401228034F9D4" authority="Li" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" box="[511,803,1598,1624]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similalbifusa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560A6949C9E401228014F9D4" box="[511,771,1598,1624]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="65">Teliphasa similalbifusa</emphasis>
Li
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="757F4B36560A6949CB5D01228756F9D4" author="Liu, L. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H." box="[838,1089,1598,1624]" pageId="5" pageNumber="65" pagination="119 - 137" refId="ref5167" refString="Liu, L., Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H. (2016) Taxonomic review of the genus Teliphasa Moore, 1888 from China, with descriptions of four new species (Lepidoptera, Pyralidae, Epipaschiinae). ZooKeys, 554, 119 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 554.6177" type="journal article" year="2016">Liu, Wang &amp; Li, 2016</bibRefCitation>
. In 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560A6949CC72012387CFF9D4" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" box="[1129,1240,1598,1624]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamata">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560A6949CC72012387CFF9D4" box="[1129,1240,1598,1624]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="65">T. hamata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
no sexual dimorphism is reported. Female genitalia (
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560A6949CA2A017E8195F9F0" box="[561,642,1634,1660]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1347,1371]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,193,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-29@5.[159,1428,181,1323]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Female genitalia of Teliphasa spp. 11, T. nubilosa; 12, T. hamata; 13, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577738" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577738/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="65">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
) with posterior apophyses 2/3rd of anterior apophyses, thicker; antrum rectangular, heavily sclerotized; ductus bursae zig-zag, weakly sclerotized posteriorly; corpus bursae pyriform, signum nearly rectangular, with multiple minute spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
